---
<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title="What is an ETF? The Complete Guide for Investors"
  description="Learn what an Exchange Traded Fund (ETF) is, how they compare to mutual funds, and the mechanics of creation and redemption."
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/what-is-etf"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>What is an ETF?</h1>
      <p>Understanding Exchange Traded Funds, Creation/Redemption, and their advantages over Mutual Funds.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="intro-section">
      <p>An Exchange Traded Fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund and exchange-traded product that tracks an index, sector, commodity, or other asset. They can be purchased or sold on a stock exchange the same way that a regular stock can. Over the past two decades, ETFs have revolutionized the investment landscape by offering individuals a low-cost, tax-efficient, and highly liquid way to diversify their portfolios.</p>
      <p>Whether you're exploring the broader <a href="/investing-glossary">Investing Glossary</a> or diving deep into specific metrics like <a href="/what-is-dividend-yield">Dividend Yield</a>, understanding ETFs is essential for modern portfolio construction.</p>
    </section>

    <h2>How Do ETFs Work?</h2>
    <p>At their core, ETFs are baskets of securities. When you buy a share of an ETF, you are buying a proportional share of that basket. For example, an S&P 500 ETF holds shares of all 500 companies in the index. As the underlying assets fluctuate in price, the value of the ETF fluctuates correspondingly.</p>

    <h3>Key Advantages of ETFs</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Diversification:</strong> By holding dozens, hundreds, or even thousands of underlying securities, ETFs spread risk.</li>
      <li><strong>Low Costs:</strong> Because most ETFs passively track an index, they have lower administrative and management costs compared to actively managed mutual funds.</li>
      <li><strong>Liquidity and Trading Flexibility:</strong> They can be bought and sold at any time during the trading day at the current market price, allowing investors to use limit orders, stop-loss orders, and even buy on margin.</li>
      <li><strong>Tax Efficiency:</strong> Due to their unique creation/redemption process, ETFs typically generate fewer capital gains distributions than mutual funds.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>ETFs vs. Mutual Funds</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <p>While both ETFs and mutual funds offer pooled investment vehicles, they differ in several critical ways:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trading:</strong> ETFs trade intraday on an exchange. Mutual funds trade once per day at the end-of-day Net Asset Value (NAV).</li>
        <li><strong>Management Style:</strong> The vast majority of ETFs are passively managed index funds. While index mutual funds exist, a large percentage of mutual funds are actively managed, seeking to beat the market (often unsuccessfully) and charging higher fees.</li>
        <li><strong>Minimum Investment:</strong> Mutual funds often require a minimum initial investment (e.g., $1,000 or $3,000). ETFs can be purchased for the price of a single share, and many brokers now offer fractional shares.</li>
        <li><strong>Taxation:</strong> Mutual funds must sell holdings to meet redemptions, potentially triggering capital gains for all shareholders. ETFs use an "in-kind" redemption process, largely avoiding this issue.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you're interested in how regular contributions into these funds can grow your wealth, read our guide on <a href="/what-is-dollar-cost-averaging">Dollar Cost Averaging</a>.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Creation and Redemption Process</h2>
    <p>The secret sauce that makes an ETF function efficiently is the creation and redemption process. This mechanism ensures that the ETF's share price remains very close to the net asset value (NAV) of its underlying holdings.</p>
    <p>This process is handled by large financial institutions known as Authorized Participants (APs).</p>

    <h3>Creation</h3>
    <p>When demand for an ETF increases, driving its price above the NAV of its underlying assets (a premium), the AP will buy the underlying securities in the open market. The AP then delivers this basket of securities to the ETF issuer in exchange for newly created shares of the ETF (typically in blocks of 50,000 shares called a "Creation Unit"). The AP sells these new ETF shares on the open market, pocketing a small arbitrage profit and driving the ETF price back down in line with its NAV.</p>

    <h3>Redemption</h3>
    <p>Conversely, if investors are selling the ETF, driving its price below the NAV (a discount), the AP will buy ETF shares on the open market. The AP delivers these shares to the ETF issuer and receives the underlying basket of securities in return. The AP then sells the individual securities on the open market. This reduces the supply of ETF shares, driving the price back up to match the NAV.</p>

    <h2>Types of ETFs</h2>
    <p>The ETF market has expanded significantly, offering exposure to virtually every asset class:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Broad Market Index ETFs:</strong> Track major indices like the S&P 500, TSX Composite, or total global stock market.</li>
      <li><strong>Sector and Industry ETFs:</strong> Focus on specific areas like technology, healthcare, or energy.</li>
      <li><strong>Bond ETFs:</strong> Provide exposure to government, corporate, or municipal bonds.</li>
      <li><strong>Commodity ETFs:</strong> Track the price of physical commodities like gold, silver, or oil.</li>
      <li><strong>Factor and Smart Beta ETFs:</strong> Screen stocks based on specific characteristics, such as low <a href="/what-is-pe-ratio">P/E Ratios</a> (Value) or high momentum.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="card FAQ">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How does an ETF differ from a mutual fund?</summary>
        <p>ETFs trade on stock exchanges throughout the day like individual stocks, while mutual funds only trade once a day at the market close at their net asset value (NAV).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the creation and redemption process?</summary>
        <p>This is the mechanism that keeps ETF share prices in line with their underlying asset values. Authorized Participants (APs) create new shares by delivering a basket of underlying securities to the ETF issuer, and redeem them by doing the reverse.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Are ETFs good for beginners?</summary>
        <p>Yes, ETFs are excellent for beginners because they provide instant diversification, low expense ratios, and require less active management than individual stock picking.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>

